words: my son Colin was trying to get something off of the shelf...
in his closet... and he fell over backwards.
He, he, he'd stood on his shoebox instead of standing on what he was supposed to stand on... fell over
backwards, hit the back of his brainstem, his head right here... and,
um... was unconscious. His, his wife came home and found him
unconscious... and, um, the police called me...
and, um, you know, told me there was an accident. When I got over
there... it was just... a horrible experience. There
was police all over the place. One looked me right in the eye and said, "That guy's dead."
Um... it just... I... it was just devastating.
Um... they took him to... El Camino Hospital,
and they... hooked him up to these machines, and we could see that he didn't have any
brain activity at all. And, um... so...
so we had Kaiser at the time, and they decided to go ahead and just leave him there at that hospital,
cause... they figured he was gonna pass. But, um... like, the head...
brain guy at El Camino Hospital came in and said, you know, there's not much
hope, and... um... you know, there's nothing we can do.
And, you know... they were trying to get me to sign these papers... so that he could donate his
organs. But, uh, I... I... I just couldn't do it.
And, um... I... I just...
sat there and just talked to him, and his wife just sat there and talked to him. And about...
the next day... um... the, the...
they did another scan... and they said it, it looked like the brain was
regenerating itself. And then Kaiser came... and got him, and took him
over to their hospital, and he spent several weeks in intensive care. And,
um, he was in a coma. So, um...
we'd go over there every day, and... you know, I'd see all these...
like, when people are in a coma, like, it isn't like it is on TV.
Um, what they did was, when he started to come out of the coma, they actually tied
him to the bed, cause cause, well he's big, and they didn't want him to, like... um, you
know. Cause he was, like, trashing around, and it was... just really scary,
and I just felt really bad. And then they took him... from Kaiser
to, um... to Kaiser in Vallejo Hospital.
They took him about... they... they took him to Kaiser Vallejo Hospital, because
there's a place there where they do, um, brain injury people.
And what they did there was... he went there in...
the back of an ambulance, and within one week, they had him walking, they had him
talking. They were teaching him all...
everything again, so he could learn, you know, how to, like, talk and
